<body>
	<div class="banner">
		<center><font color="white" size="16px" face="arial">CytR</font></center>
	</div>
	<div align="center" class="main-content">
		<div class="spacer">
	</div><br>			<label class="collapse_ACT" for="_1"><font size="5px">CytR transcriptional activity</font></label>
				<input id="_1" type="checkbox">
				<div class="ACT"><br><ul><li>Keywords : Uridine phosphorylase structure ; Gamma-proteobacteria ; Heterologous expression ; CytR regulation 1 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , genes coding for transcriptional-repressor CytR , nitrite reductase , 2-dexoyribose-5-phosphate aldolase , thymidine phosphorylase , lysine/cadaverine transport protein , putrescine / ornithine antiporter , ornithine decarboxylase , ethanola-mine operon , and propanediol operon as well as its transcriptional-regulator PocR were activated by ArcA ( Figure 3B and 3C , and Additional file 1 : Table S1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21418628" target="_blank">21418628</a>]<br></li>
<li>CytR and CRP proteins were added to the following ﬁnal concentrations : Lanes 1 , no proteins ; 2 , 1.3 nM CytR ; 3 , 0.4 nM CRP ; 4 , 4.2 nM CRP ; 5 , 0.65 nM CytR and 0.2 nM CRP .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>As shown in Table 3 , CytR regulation was reduced from approximately 8-fold in udpPEc and udpPSt to approximately 3-fold in udpPYp , and to 1.6-fold in udpPV c whereas cAMP -- CRP activation was approximately the same in all promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>In CytR regulated promoters , including the udpP promoter , the cAMP -- CRP complex acts as a transcriptional-activator as well as a co-repressor for the CytR protein [ 5,23,25 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>The CytR repressor both contacts DNA and the cAMP receptor protein when binding to the deoP2 promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=22435712" target="_blank">22435712</a>]<br></li>
<li>One promoter is regulated negatively by the DeoR repressor , and the other is regulated negatively by the CytR repressor and positively by the cAMP/CRP complex ( Bremer et al. 1988 ; Gerlach et al. 1990 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16489221" target="_blank">16489221</a>]<br></li>
<li>Both cdd and udp are members of the CytR regulon , i.e. , the expression of these genes is negatively regulated by the CytR repressor protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>In order to analyze the possibility that CytR afﬁnity to different promoters was mediated by their ability to-bind cAMP -- CRP , gel retardation experiments with the same 32P-end-labeled DNA fragments were performed in the presence of puriﬁed E. coli CRP protein ( Fig. 6 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression of heterlogous udp promoters in E. coli cells To verify the level of CytR regulation and cAMP -- CRP activation of heterologous promoters we constructed a series of plasmids carrying the udpP -- lacZ transcriptional fusions ( plasmids pMZ32 , pMZ37 , pMZ39 and pMZ43 , see Materials and methods ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>Moreover , the efﬁciency of E. coli CytR protein to-bind udpPV c increased markedly in the presence of cAMP -- CRP .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>It therefore appears that the maximal reduction of CytR regulation observed in the case of udpPV c is most likely a con sequence of the combined effect of the absence of a CytR consensus sequence and the presence of an improved CRP1 binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>In summary , this work conﬁrms previous reports on CRP and CytR regulation which show that bacteria use activating and repressing modules in different stoichiometric and structural arrangements to differentially adjust the expression of genes belonging to the same regulon [ 32 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , these data strongly suggest that the reduced CytR regulation of udpPYp and udpPV c was due to reduced CytR binding .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , udpPV c which was characterized by maximal reduction of CytR regulation and titration in vivo , also exhibited the lowest ability to-bind CytR in vitro .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_DOM" for="_2"><font size="5px">CytR protein domains</font></label>
				<input id="_2" type="checkbox">
				<div class="DOM"><br><ul><li>As shown in Fig. 3 , the corresponding region of udpPSt contained a very similar putative CytR binding site , while neither udpPYp nor udpPV c contained inverted repeats or a TGCA motif between positions − 71 / − 67 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>It was shown that the DNA-binding domain of the E. coli CytR protein includes the N-terminal 57 residues [ 28 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>Mutational analysis of E. coli udpP promoter revealed that the pentameric motif TGCA played a key role in binding the CytR repressor to udpPEc [ 38 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>Firstly , from the analysis of udpP it has ′ Ec been proposed that the pentamer 5 - TGCAA plays an important role in sequence-speciﬁc DNA-binding of CytR [ 5,38 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">CytR evolution</font></label>
				<input id="_3" type="checkbox">
				<div class="EVO"><br><ul><li>It should be noted that V. cholerae CytR exhibits a high level of homology throughout the protein ( 81 % similarity and 65 % identity ) with the CytR protein of E. coli but contains deletion of the ﬁrst 8 amino acids in the N-terminal region of protein [ 10 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_RP" for="_4"><font size="5px">Processes regulated by CytR</font></label>
				<input id="_4" type="checkbox">
				<div class="RP"><br><ul><li>[ 10 ] A.J. Haugo , P.I. Watnick , Vibrio cholerae CytR is a repressor of bioﬁlm development , Mol .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>Repression of deoP2 in Escherichia coli by CytR : conversion of a transcription activator into a repressor .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14526015" target="_blank">14526015</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , genes coding for transcriptional repressor CytR , nitrite reductase , 2-dexoyribose-5-phosphate aldolase , thymidine phosphorylase , lysine/cadaverine-transport protein , putrescine / ornithine antiporter , ornithine decarboxylase , ethanola-mine operon , and propanediol operon as well as its transcriptional regulator PocR were activated by ArcA ( Figure 3B and 3C , and Additional file 1 : Table S1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21418628" target="_blank">21418628</a>]<br></li>
<li>In E. coli , the structural gene udp encoding UPase is a member of the CytR regulon which comprises at least nine transcriptional units that encode proteins involved in nucleoside uptake and metabolism [ 9 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>In CytR regulated promoters , including the udpP promoter , the cAMP -- CRP complex acts as a transcriptional activator as well as a co-repressor for the CytR protein [ 5,23,25 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_SIT" for="_5"><font size="5px">CytR binding site</font></label>
				<input id="_5" type="checkbox">
				<div class="SIT"><br><ul><li>In one mode , CytR recognizes inverted octamer repeats separated by 10 -- 13 bp ( inverted-repeats , L-10 / 13-R site : ( A/T ) ( G/C ) TGCAAC-10 / 13-GTT ( G/A ) CATT ) ; in another the repressor binds direct optamer repeats separated by 1 bp ( R-1R : GTTGCATT-1-GTTGCAC ) [ 23 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>As shown in Fig. 3 , the corresponding region of udpPSt contained a very similar putative CytR binding site , while neither udpPYp nor udpPV c contained inverted-repeats or a TGCA motif between positions − 71 / − 67 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>The CytR operator in udpPEc was located between the two CRP sites and consisted of an imperfect inverted-repeat ( Fig. 3 ) [ 5 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>The operators recognized by DeoR and CytR are present in the sequence of the S. Typhi tsx promoter , and the deoR and cytR genes are conserved in the S. Typhi genome sequence ( Parkhill et al. 2001 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16489221" target="_blank">16489221</a>]<br></li>
<li>Comparative analysis of the udpP promoter region from Y. pseudotuberculosis , V. cholerae , S. typhimurium and E. coli revealed that location , spacing and orientation of putative binding sites for CRP protein are highly conserved , whereas CytR protein recognition sequences of udpPYp and udpPV c deviate markedly from the E. coli and S. typhimurium CytR binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>The absence of consensus sequences for the CytR protein within the udp regulatory region of Y. pseudotuberculosis and V. cholerae ( Fig. 3 ) suggests that reduced CytR regulation of udpPYp and udpPV c was due to the reduced ability of the E. coli CytR protein to bind heterlogous promoters Fig. 3 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>It therefore appears that the maximal reduction of CytR regulation observed in the case of udpPV c is most likely a con sequence of the combined effect of the absence of a CytR consensus sequence and the presence of an improved CRP1 binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>The boxed sequences indicate the two CRP sites and underlined bold letters indicate the sequences sharing homology with the consensus CytR binding site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consistently , examination of the udpPYp and udpPV c sequences reveals potential CytR binding sites with sequences : AATGTATT-10-CTTTGCG and TATGAAG-10-ATTGCTGT , respectively ( Fig. 3 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
				</ul></div><br>
			<label class="collapse_TU" for="_6"><font size="5px">Transcription unit regulated by CytR</font></label>
				<input id="_6" type="checkbox">
				<div class="TU"><br><ul><li>Both cdd and udp are members of the CytR regulon , i.e. , the expression of these genes is negatively regulated by the CytR repressor protein .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14499937" target="_blank">14499937</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul></div><br>
